I think the game is too orientated towards a tiny proportion of items being
useful. scrolls of Teleport and potions of CCW are the staples that, with a
Staff of teleportation later on (barring rBlind and rConf and 0% failure anyway)
are used be everyone.

When's the last time you bought a scroll of light, object detection or trap
detection from the shops, or potions of boldness?

Or for that matter wands of, for example, sleep monster?

It seems the &quot;formulae&quot; for winning Vanilla are incredibly restrictive - now I'm
not endorsing the &quot;every item has a crazy hidden benefit&quot; that NetHack seems to
enjoy, but it would be nice that the core items could be made a fair bit more
expensive. Later on, 500 a pop for !CCW is nothing -- earlier on you have to
balance it, perhaps actually giving !CLW a buyer for the first time.

Ranger - Get arrows, enchant bow, get !CCW, !speed, ?Phase, ?Tele, and the first
two books, and waltz to 1000' without any big hassles -- You can dump most of
the rest of the items you find without any real loss.

What I'd _really_ like to see is item acid damage being temporary and
&quot;repairable&quot;, and not actually have the ability to enchant weapons or armour. It
seems so munchkinlike to grab any old weapon and scum it up to +9,+9 -- that's
supposed to be a really _good_ magical item, not a shop bought stock knife and a
few scrolls.

I think part of the TMJ problem is that such a high proportion of items are junk
from the very beginning. I reckon 80% of dungeon drops at 50' and 100' are
simply a waste of temporary memory space, and I would like to see that addressed
at some stage.

Besides which, my characters die primarily from boredom (or, in the latest
escapade with Andrew Doull's rebalanced monster patch, something new and
surprising such as the much changed Bullroarer) - the game is not actually very
difficult for people with the time and patience to slog their way through,
running whenever the chance of being in serious trouble rises above a fraction
of a percent, and happily taking 7 to 8 encounters to kill any of the serious
uniques. It is lack of patience that kills, and that seems to be a sad primary
cause of death for a game IMHO.

